  "text": "However, the tamoxifen dose in animal experimental studies is not easy to standardize because rats have a faster metabolism than humans. Equal-weight doses may not reproduce the serum levels and effects of tamoxifen in women [CITATION_1] . Dos Santos et al. [CITATION_2] , who studied the morphometry of the urethra in castrated rats given a 250 mg/day tamoxifen dose for 30 days, observed that tamoxifen was capable of increasing the uterine weight and the thickness of the distal urethral epithelium. Thus, we used a dose of 250 mg/animal/day in this study because it could mimic the effects of tamoxifen on women undergoing breast cancer treatment [CITATION_3] .",
